ps%3A%2F%2Fm-timesofindia-com.cdn.ampproject.org%2Fc%2Fs%2Fm.timesofindia.com%2Fworld%2Frest-of-world%2Fugandan-president-yoweri-museveni-praises-indian-diasporas-contribution-to-ugandas-economy%2Famp_articleshow%2F107029532.cms%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fm.timesofindia.com%2Fworld%2Frest-of-world%2Fugandan-president-yoweri-museveni-praises-indian-diasporas-contribution-to-ugandas-economy%2Famp_articleshow%2F107029532.cms%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Girish%20Karnad%20and%20The%20Mahabharata%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cimg%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F01%2F21132432%2F67b1bacb-eeaa-49a8-a168-1a3562f0e74b.jpg%5C%22%3E%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CThe%20only%20book%20he%20had%20ever%20insisted%20that%20we%20read%20%E2%80%94%20putting%20copies%20in%20our%20hands%20%E2%80%94%20was%20the%20Mahabharata.%E2%80%9D%3Cbr%3E%5Cn%E2%88%BC%20Raghu%20and%20Radha%20Karnad%2C%20Afterword%2C%20%3Cem%3EThis%20Life%20At%20Play%3C%2Fem%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%201959%2C%20when%20Girish%20Karnad%20was%20about%20to%20leave%20for%20Oxford%20as%20a%20Rhodes%20Scholar%2C%20he%20felt%20compelled%20to%20read%20the%20epics%20and%20the%20Puranas%20before%20his%20departure.%20He%20had%20grown%20up%20watching%20these%20stories%20performed%20by%20lamplight%2C%20by%20Yakshagana%20and%20Company%20Natak%20troupes.%20Now%20he%20reached%20for%20C.%20Rajagopalachari%E2%80%99s%20concise%20but%20complete%20versions%20of%20the%C2%A0%3Cem%3ERamayana%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0and%20the%C2%A0%3Cem%3EMahabharata%3C%2Fem%3E.%20This%20is%20the%20decision%20that%20would%20eventually%20lead%20him%20to%20write%20his%20first%20play%2C%C2%A0%3Cem%3EYayati%3C%2Fem%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEvery%20aspect%20of%20this%20play%20took%20him%20by%20surprise%2C%20as%20Aparna%20Dharwadker%20notes%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CThat%20it%20was%20a%20play%20and%20not%20a%20cluster%20of%20angst-ridden%20poems%2C%20that%20it%20was%20written%20in%20Kannada%20instead%20of%20English%2C%20and%20that%20it%20used%20an%20episode%20from%20the%20Mahabharata%20as%20its%20narrative%20basis.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20choice%20%E2%80%9Cnailed%20me%20to%20my%20past%2C%E2%80%9D%20Karnad%20said.%20It%20set%20him%20on%20a%20path%20of%20drawing%20narratives%20from%20myth%2C%20history%20and%20folklore%2C%20which%20dominated%20his%20playwriting%20for%20the%20next%20four%20decades.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20myth%20of%20Yayati%2C%20a%20king%20is%20cursed%20with%20decrepit%20old%20age%2C%20and%20Puru%2C%20his%20youngest%20son%2C%20agrees%20to%20bear%20the%20curse%20on%20his%20behalf.%20In%C2%A0%3Cem%3EThis%20Life%20At%20Play%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20Karnad%20recalls%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CI%20was%20excited%20by%20the%20story%20of%20Yayati%2C%20where%20a%20son%20exchanges%20his%20youth%20with%20his%20father%E2%80%99s%20old%20age.%20The%20situation%20was%20both%20dramatic%20and%20tragic.%20But%20the%20question%20that%20bothered%20me%20even%20as%20I%20was%20finishing%20the%20story%20was%3A%20If%20the%20son%20had%20been%20married%2C%20what%20would%20the%20wife%20do%3F%20Would%20she%20have%20accepted%20this%20unnatural%20arrangement%3F%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20imaginary%20character%E2%80%99s%20response%20became%20the%20seed%20of%20his%20first%20play%2C%20written%20at%20the%20age%20of%2022%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CThis%20was%20the%20first%20scene%20that%20formed%20in%20front%20of%20my%20eyes%3A%20the%20confrontation%20between%20Yayati%20and%20Chitralekha.%20%E2%80%A6%20As%20I%20thought%20about%20it%2C%20the%20rest%20of%20the%20play%20began%20to%20take%20shape%20around%20this%20climax.%20I%20did%20not%20feel%20as%20if%20I%20was%20writing%20a%20play%E2%80%A6%20It%20was%20as%20if%20a%20spirit%20had%20entered%20me.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAt%20the%20time%2C%20Karnad%20was%20a%20young%20man%20facing%20his%20own%20burdensome%20questions%3A%20Would%20he%20return%20to%20India%20when%20he%20was%20done%20at%20Oxford%3F%20What%20were%20his%20responsibilities%2C%20as%20a%20young%20man%2C%20to%20his%20own%20father%2C%20his%20family%2C%20or%20his%20country%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhen%20Karnad%20wrote%20the%20play%2C%20he%20could%20relate%20to%20the%20son%2C%20Puru%2C%20and%20the%20weight%20of%20obligation%20he%20feels%20in%20the%20story.%20When%20he%20read%20the%20play%20again%2C%20much%20later%20in%20his%20own%20life%2C%20he%20found%20himself%20identifying%20with%20the%20desperation%20of%20the%20father.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWatch%3A%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fyoutu.be%2FzvrEPHuVTZo%3Fsi%3DAta_8Q2EA3mEDi7o%5C%22%3EThe%20Structure%20of%20the%20Play%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20a%20lecture%20by%20Karnad%20on%C2%A0%3Cem%3EYayati%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0at%20the%20Sahitya%20Rangabhoomi%20Pratishthan%20in%202015.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20second%20story%20from%20the%20Mahabharata%20also%20made%20an%20impression%20on%20Karnad%20at%20that%20early%20point.%20This%20one%2C%20though%2C%20would%20take%2037%20years%20to%20become%20a%20play%3A%C2%A0%3Cem%3EAgni%20Mattu%20Mal%C3%A9%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20or%C2%A0%3Cem%3EThe%20Fire%20and%20the%20Rain%3C%2Fem%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F01%2F21132709%2F965c8b05-a7a4-451c-aa20-77de271189e6.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%221200%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F01%2F21132709%2F965c8b05-a7a4-451c-aa20-77de271189e6.jpg%201200w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F01%2F21132709%2F965c8b05-a7a4-451c-aa20-77de271189e6-300x200.jpg%20300w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F01%2F21132709%2F965c8b05-a7a4-451c-aa20-77de271189e6-1024x683.jpg%201024w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-693865%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22800%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EThe%20Fire%20and%20the%20Rain%2C%20Nagna%20Udupi.%20Courtesy%3A%20The%20World%20of%20Girish%20Karnad%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAnmol%20Tikoo%2C%20who%20co-hosted%20the%20interview%20podcast%2C%C2%A0%3Cem%3EThe%20River%20Has%20No%20Fear%20Of%20Memories%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20tells%20us%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CGirish%20Karnad%E2%80%99s%20mythic%20plays%20are%20bookended%20by%20the%20Mahabharata%20%E2%80%94%20%3Cem%3EYayati%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0at%20one%20end%2C%20and%20the%3Cem%3E%C2%A0Fire%20and%20the%20Rain%C2%A0%3C%2Fem%3Eat%20the%20other.%20In%20the%20podcast%2C%20he%20told%20us%20how%20most%20of%20his%20plays%20(Yayati%20being%20the%20exception)%20didn%E2%80%99t%20just%20come%20to%20him%2C%20how%20he%20chose%20to%20meticulously%20enrich%20his%20traditions.%20Like%20modernist%20writers%20before%20him%2C%20he%20looked%20to%20the%20epics%20for%20inspiration%2C%20and%20arguably%20the%20Mahabharata%20was%20one%20of%20his%20%E2%80%9Cakshaya%20patras.%E2%80%9D%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20myth%20of%20Yavakri(ta)%20would%20sit%20with%20Karnad%20until%201993%2C%20when%C2%A0%3Cem%3EThe%20Fire%20and%20the%20Rain%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0was%20commissioned%20by%20the%20Guthrie%20Theatre%2C%20which%20had%20just%20staged%20the%20first%20professional%20US%20performance%20of%C2%A0%3Cem%3ENagamandala%3C%2Fem%3E.%20He%20wrote%20it%20in%20Kannada%2C%20and%20translated%20it%20into%20English%20right%20afterward.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CThe%20split%20between%20nature%20and%20culture%2C%20body%20and%20mind%20appears%20in%20such%20earlier%20plays%20as%C2%A0%3Cem%3EHayavadana%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0and%C2%A0%3Cem%3EBali%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20but%20in%C2%A0%3Cem%3EAgni%20Mattu%20Male%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0the%20duality%20is%20expressed%20for%20the%20first%20time%20as%20the%20explicit%20opposition%20between%20brahmin%20and%20shudra%2C%E2%80%9D%20Aparna%20Dharwadker%20observes.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHere%E2%80%99s%20Anmol%20Tikoo%20again%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CIn%20the%20%3Cem%3EFire%20and%20the%20Rain%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20he%20creates%20this%20intricate%20structure%2C%20including%20a%20play%20within%20the%20play%2C%20that%20allows%20us%20to%20look%20beyond%20the%20elites%20and%20their%20obsessions.%20This%20is%20the%20fire%20versus%20the%20rain%20%E2%80%94%20the%20Agni%20of%20the%20dominant%20castes%20and%20their%20scriptures%2C%20versus%20the%20Male%20of%20ordinary%20folks%2C%20their%20art%20and%20their%20concerns.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIf%20Mahabharata%20is%20about%20the%20difficulty%20of%20being%20good%2C%20then%C2%A0%3Cem%3EFire%20and%20the%20Rain%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0gives%20a%20positive%20counter%20to%20that%20in%20the%20transgressive%20love%20of%20Arvasu%20and%20Nittilai.%20Caring%20for%20others%2C%20those%20who%20aren%E2%80%99t%20akin%20to%20us%2C%20is%20what%20keeps%20the%20world%20going%20and%20that%20is%20what%20turns%20out%20to%20be%20the%20natural%20order%20of%20things.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EListen%20to%C2%A0%3Ca%20rel%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fbangaloreinternationalcentre.org%2Faudio%2F182-girishkarnad8-9-the-river-has-no-fear-of-memories-being-an-existentialist%2F%5C%22%3Eepisode%208%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0of%C2%A0%3Cem%3EThe%20River%20Has%20No%20Fear%20of%20Memories%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20where%20Karnad%20speaks%20to%20Tikoo%20and%20Arshia%20Sattar%20about%20the%20Mahabharata%2C%20history%2C%20and%20much%20more.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThe%20Fire%20and%20the%20Rain%3C%2Fem%3E%C2%A0evoked%20a%20rare%20%E2%80%9Cintensity%20of%20responses%2C%20both%20negative%20and%20positive%2C%E2%80%9D%20Dharwadker%20writes%2C%20which%20are%20easily%20explained%3A%20%E2%80%9CIt%20is%20a%20dense%2C%20intellectually%20ambitious%2C%20autumnal%20play%20structured%20around%20ideas%E2%80%A6%20and%20a%20plethora%20of%20tangled%20relationships%20which%20unfold%20with%20a%20rare%20economy%20and%20intensity%20of%20words%20and%20emotions.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20472px)%2085vw%2C%20472px%5C%22%20